doc.ContractDescription: IN RECENT YEARS AN ENORMOUS TROVE OF DATA HAS BEEN COLLECTED IN FIELD CAMPAIGNS AIMED AT TO STUDYING HURRICANE DYNAMICS (GRIP AND HS3), PRECIPITATION MICROPHYSICAL PROCESSES (MC3E AND GCPEX), AND PRECIPITATION-HYDROLOGIC INTERACTIONS (IPHEX). EACH OF THESE FIELD CAMPAIGNS EMPLOYED MULTIPLE AIRBORNE (AND IN SOME CASES, GROUND-BASED) RADARS AND RADIOMETERS FEATURING MULTIPLE FREQUENCIES AND COMPLEX VIEWING GEOMETRY, WITH MISMATCHED AND OVERLAPPING BEAMS. THE MULTI-INSTRUMENT INVERSE SOLVER TESTBED (MIIST) TOOL WILL BE USED TO DELVE INTO THE DIVERSE DATASETS PROVIDED BY PAST AND CURRENT PRECIPITATION GROUND VALIDATION EXPERIMENTS, AND WILL ALSO BE ADAPTABLE ENOUGH TO BE USED FOR FUTURE MISSIONS. A THREE-DIMENSIONAL VECTOR RADIATIVE TRANSFER MODEL CAPABLE OF SIMULATING MULTIPLE SCATTERING AND MULTIPLE POLARIZATIONS AT MICROWAVE FREQUENCIES (3-300 GHZ) WILL BE THE BASIS FOR MIIST.
